Airbnb Problem Definition¶

Context¶

Airbnb is an online platform that allows people to rent short-term accommodation. This ranges from regular people with a spare bedroom to property management firms who lease multiple rentals. On the one side, Airbnb enables owners to list their space and earn rental money. On the other side, it provides travellers easy access to renting private homes. Airbnb receives commissions from two sources upon every booking, namely from the hosts and guests. For every booking, Airbnb charges the guest 6-12% of the booking fee. Moreover, Airbnb charges the host 3% for every successful transaction. As a senior data scientist at Airbnb, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the Rent for accommodation and can help hosts, travellers, and also the business in devising profitable strategies.

Objective¶

To explore and visualize the data, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of Airbnb rental rooms, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains information about the different types of rental rooms offered by Airbnb over a fixed period of time. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • id: Property ID
  • room_type: Type of Room in the property
  • accommodates: How many adults can this property accommodate
  • bathrooms: Number of bathrooms on the property
  • cancellation_policy: Cancellation policy of the property
  • cleaning_fee: This denotes whether the property cleaning fee is included in the rent or not
  • instant_bookable: It indicates whether an instant booking facility is available or not
  • review_scores_rating: Review rating score of the property
  • bedrooms: Number of bedrooms in the property
  • beds: Total number of beds in the property
  • log_price: Log of the rental price of the property for a fixed period. [If the price is 12000 dollars, then log_price represents log(12000)]

Observations

  • room_type There are 3 different room types. Entire home/apt is most commonly available.
  • accomodates The rentals have accomodations available for 1 person to maximum of 16 people. 50% of them accomodate 2 people and 75% of them aaccomodate more than 2 people.
  • bathrooms minimum number of bathrooms is 0, in reality an accomodation cannot be without bathrooms, we may have to treat the 0s and try replacing them with median values. Maximum number of bathrooms are 8.
  • cancellation_policy There are 3 different types of cancellation policies, most of them are strict.
  • cleaning_fee Cleaning fee must be a True/False boolean value, most of their rentals have a cleaning fee.
  • Similarly instant_bookable also looks like a t or f (true or false) boolean value, most of the rentals cannot be booked at an instant.
  • review_scores_rating AirBnB accomodations have a minimum rating of 20 and a maximum rating of 100, so we can consider the ratings to be in the scale of 20 and 100.
  • Rest of the fields have missing values, bathrooms, bedrooms, beds and price columns have 0 as values, we have to handle them first before proceeding with further analysis. It is not possible to have accomodations without bathrooms, bedrooms and 0 price.

  • log_price we may not get the expected result since there are 0s in the log_price.

# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot
In [1816]:
# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Summary of EDA¶

Data Description:

  • The target variable (log_price) is of float type.
  • room_type, accommodates, bathrooms, cleaning_fee, cancellation_policy,instant_bookable,bedrooms,beds seem to have finite set of values, probably they can be considered as categorical values. Let us find out the disctinct values in these columns and decide based on that.
  • review_scores_rating seem to have a range of values, let us find out the min and max range for this column.
  • log_price column might need some processing, let us do some processing and see what the actual price looks like.
  • The column data types seem to be aligned with the values in the columns, categorical values have been converted to category data type and dummy values have been created.

Data Cleaning:

  • id column is just an index column, as this does not have any value to our model, so we can drop this column.
  • Except log_price and instant_bookable columns the rest of the columns have missing values.
  • The review_scores_rating column has the most number of missing values.
  • accomodates - group by median for missing values
  • room_type replace missing values of room type as Entire home/apt if the rental property can accomodate 4 or more people
  • replace missing values of room type as Private room if the rental property can accomodate between 2 to 3 persons
  • if the room accomodates only one person then it is a Private room

cleaning_fee

  • since, majority of rental properties have cleaning fee
  • we can assign the majority value for the missing values

cancellation_policy

  • majority of properties have strict cancellation
  • we can assign the majority value for the missing values

bedrooms

  • single bedroom rentals can accomodate upto 4 people.
  • Rentals having 2 to 3 bedrooms can accomodate upto 9 people
  • For accomodating 10 people or more the rentals have 4 or more bedrooms.
  • Taking this into consideration, we can set the missing bedroom counts accordingly.

bathrooms

  • From the group by median data 2 bathrooms for accomodations between 6 and 11. For accomodations more than 11, consider 3 bathrooms.

beds

  • Single bed can accomodate upto 3 people
  • 2 beds for 4 people
  • Between 5 and 6 people 3 beds are needed
  • Between 7 and 8 people 4 beds are needed,
  • 9 and 10 people = 5 beds
  • 11 and 12 people = 6 beds
  • To accomodate 13 and above 7 beds are required

review_scores

  • It looks like the average rating for all the room types is above 90. Which means most of the accomodations have an excellent score.
  • This data seems to have lot of outliers.
  • This column has been binned for better analysis.

log_price

  • Do inverse log on Price column to find the actual price.

Duplicates:

There were 23633 duplicate rows, they have been dropped.

Observations

  • room_type There are 3 different room types. Entire home/apt is most commonly available.
  • accomodates The rentals have accomodations available for 1 person to maximum of 16 people. 50% of them accomodate 2 people and 75% of them aaccomodate more than 2 people.
  • bathrooms minimum number of bathrooms is 0, in reality an accomodation cannot be without bathrooms, we may have to treat the 0s and try replacing them with median values. Maximum number of bathrooms are 8.
  • cancellation_policy There are 3 different types of cancellation policies, most of them are strict.
  • cleaning_fee Cleaning fee must be a True/False boolean value, most of their rentals have a cleaning fee.
  • Similarly instant_bookable also looks like a t or f (true or false) boolean value, most of the rentals cannot be booked at an instant.
  • review_scores_rating AirBnB accomodations have a minimum rating of 20 and a maximum rating of 100, so we can consider the ratings to be in the scale of 20 and 100.
  • Rest of the fields have missing values, bathrooms, bedrooms, beds and price columns have 0 as values, we have to handle them first before proceeding with further analysis. It is not possible to have accomodations without bathrooms, bedrooms and 0 price.
  • log_price we may not get the expected result since there are 0s in the log_price.

6.Linear Regression - Model building¶

Model performance check¶

  • We will be using metric functions defined in sklearn for RMSE, MAE, and $R^2$.

  • We will define functions to calculate adjusted $R^2$ and MAPE.

    • The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) measures the accuracy of predictions as a percentage, and can be calculated as the average absolute percent error for each predicted value minus actual values divided by actual values. It works best if there are no extreme values in the data and none of the actual values are 0.

  • We will create a function that will print out all the above metrics in one go.

Function to compute adjusted R-squared¶

In [1851]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

7.Forward Feature Selection¶

Forward feature selection starts with an empty model and adds in variables one by one.

  • In each forward step, you add the one variable that gives the single best improvement to your model.
  • We'll use forward feature selection on all the variables.
In [1906]:
df_sfs = pd.get_dummies(
    df_sfs,
    columns=df_sfs.select_dtypes(include=["object", "category"]).columns.tolist(),
    drop_first=True,
)

from mlxtend.feature_selection import SequentialFeatureSelector as SFS
reg = LinearRegression()

# Build step forward feature selection
sfs = SFS(
    reg,
    k_features=x_train.shape[1],
    forward=True,  # k_features denotes "Number of features to select"
    floating=False,
    scoring="r2",
    cv=5,
)

# Perform SFFS
sfs = sfs.fit(x_train, y_train)

  • Linear Regression with Log Transform and Sequential Feature selection seem to have better prediction than rest of the models.

  • There is a very verly slight improvement with SFS

Observations

  • The negative values in price difference denotes that the predicted price is more than the actual price.
  • From the scattered plot we see that the Private_room accomodations have been predicted to be over priced than the actual price
  • Though shared accommodations are very minimal, their prices seem to be way off too.

Actionable Insights & Business Recommendations¶

Insights for Hosts

  • The number of bedrooms, bathrooms and number of accomodations does not seem to be proportiante.
  • Increase in the number of bedrooms and bathrooms for more accomodations will attract more customers.
  • Rentals with Entire home/appartment is more widely used, most of them seem to be priced higher.
  • Some of the shared accomodations are priced equally to entire home or appartment, there is a potential for customers to move to Entire home or apartment type, so price reasonably.

Insights for Travellers

  • Instant booking options are available in most of the rentals to help planning the travel easier.

Business recommendations for making profitable AirBnB business

  • Price is slightly higher when there is a cleaning fee, there could be potentail loss of customer so reducing the cleaning fee might help.
  • Price is slightly higher when the cancellation policy is strict, there could be potentail loss of customer so being flexible on cancellation policy might attract more customers.
  • Price is slightly higher when the rental cannot be booked at an instant, this can be kept as it is, because the demand may be higher for instant booking.
  • It also appears that good review rating has more probablity of creating demand and hence a better price.

There appears to be a trend away from shared living arrangements like private rooms, more instant booking, and the increased use of Airbnb as a business venture rather than as an opportunity to personally connect with a guest, further reducing interactions between hosts and guests.
